The episode of Joan ol Arc was vexatious, and led to the raising ol the siege os Orleans, and the occupation of Rheims. But in lact, no army ol English, however numerous and however well appointed, could have kept France in sub· jection. It would have been necessary to garrison every town with English troops, at least in other than the hereditary dominions of the Plantagenet kings, and to have secured the constant services ol a strong ally on the mainland. For a time the English had such an ally in the Duke os Burgundy. But when the alliance was broken by the raid on Calais, and the death ol Bedsord, the hope os occupying France was gone, and the utmost which the exertions ol the English could expect was the retention ol Normandy and Guienne, the connecting link of which was Anjou and Maine.

The possession of Normandy was, according to the policy of Eng- land in the fifteenth century, and indeed for a long time afterwards, os signal importance. It enabled the English navy to keep the mastery of the narrow seas, and the control over those seas was equivalent to the control of all commerce by sea. This is shown with great clear- ness and detail in that remarkable political tract, published in the Rolls' Series, among other political songs and ballads of the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries, by the late Mr. Wright, under the title of ‘A Libel os English Policy.’ The whole mercantile marine of Europe was engaged in coasting along France to the Low Countries‚ with the exception of that—already almost lost, owing to the decline of the Greek empne-which passed up the Danube, and that which was carried on the highway ol the Rhine.
